<body><h1 style="font-size: 50px;"><center>THE FAULT IN OUR STARS</center></h1>
    <h3 style="padding-left: 700px; font-size: 35px;">-JOHN GREEN</h3>
    <center><img src="https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1660273739i/11870085.jpg" width="450px" height="600px"></center>
    <h2><center><b>Publication Date: 10 January,2012</b><br><b>Pages:313</b><br><b>Awards:Premio Bartolom√© Hidalgo</b></center></h2>
    <h4>The Fault in Our Stars by John Green is a poignant and heartfelt novel that explores themes of love, loss, and the search for meaning in the face of terminal illness. The story follows Hazel Grace Lancaster, a sixteen-year-old cancer patient who meets and falls in love with Augustus Waters, a charming and witty fellow cancer survivor, at a support group. Together, they embark on a journey to meet Hazel's favorite author, which leads to a deeper understanding of their lives and each other. <br>

        Green's writing is both engaging and thought-provoking, capturing the complexity of teenage emotions and the stark realities of living with a life-threatening disease. The characters are well-developed and relatable, with Hazel's introspective nature and Augustus's optimism creating a compelling dynamic that drives the narrative forward. <br>
        
        The novel's strength lies in its ability to balance humor and tragedy, offering readers moments of levity amidst the heavier themes. Green's use of metaphors and symbolic imagery adds depth to the story, making it not just a tale of illness but a profound commentary on the human experience. <br>
        
        Overall, The Fault in Our Stars is a moving and memorable read that resonates long after the final page. It challenges readers to consider the fragility of life and the importance of cherishing every moment, making it a standout work in contemporary young adult fiction.
    </h4>
